@specul8 I made an undocumented experimental change in the latest commit. Try running shai-hulud-detector.sh with the `--use-git-grep` flag.
I tested it on a  large repo and, for me, it was twice as fast as ripgrep.
Hopefully it works for you 🤞

## Implementation Details - Inline Code Explanations

### 1. AllowlistEntry Interface (src/types.ts:95)

The `AllowlistEntry` interface defines the structure for allowlist entries:

```typescript
export interface AllowlistEntry {
  type?: SecurityFindingType;    // Optional - acts as wildcard if omitted
  severity?: 'critical' | 'high' | 'medium' | 'low';
  title?: string;                // Exact match
  titleContains?: string;        // Substring match
  location?: string;             // Exact match
  locationContains?: string;     // Substring match
  evidenceContains?: string;     // Substring match
  comment?: string;              // Documentation only - not used in matching
}
```

**Key Design**: All fields are optional to support flexible matching patterns.

---

### 2. Fail-Fast Error Handling (src/allowlist.ts:47)

Per @buggedcom's feedback, malformed JSON **FAILS the scan**:

```typescript
try {
  parsed = JSON.parse(content);
} catch (error) {
  throw new Error(`Invalid JSON in allowlist file "${filePath}": ${error.message}`);
}
```

**Rationale**: Silently ignoring a broken allowlist could let critical findings slip through unnoticed.

---

### 3. AND-Based Matching Logic (src/allowlist.ts:80)

All specified fields must match (AND logic):

```typescript
function matchesFinding(finding: SecurityFinding, entry: AllowlistEntry): boolean {
  if (entry.type \!== undefined && entry.type \!== finding.type) return false;
  if (entry.severity \!== undefined && entry.severity \!== finding.severity) return false;
  // ... more field checks ...
  return true;  // Only if ALL specified fields match
}
```

**Key Design**: Early-return on any mismatch prevents overly broad exclusions.

---

### 4. Integration Point (src/index.ts:270)

Allowlist processing happens AFTER `runScan()` but BEFORE output/annotations:

```typescript
// Run the scan
const summary = runScan(...);

// ALLOWLIST PROCESSING - modifies summary in-place
if (\!inputs.ignoreAllowlist) {
  allowlist = loadAllowlist(allowlistPath);
  if (allowlist.length > 0) {
    allowlistResult = applyAllowlist(...);
    summary.securityFindings = allowlistResult.filteredFindings;  // Filter in-place
    summary.results = allowlistResult.filteredResults;
  }
}

// All downstream code uses filtered summary automatically
switch (inputs.outputFormat) { ... }
```

**Key Design**: By modifying the summary object directly, all downstream code (output, annotations, failure logic) automatically uses filtered results.

